[2]
Date: Tue 29 May 2007
Source: Welsh Assembly Government, most recent press releases
[accessed 3 Jun 2007, edited]
<http://new.wales.gov.uk/news/presreleasearchive/1473127/?lang=en>

Test results for the H7N2 strain of avian flu from poultry on a farm
on the Llyn Peninsula have proved negative. The final results
received today [29 May 2007] by the Welsh Assembly Government confirm
that birds on the farm are not infected with this virus.
Birds on the farm were tested because of a connection with Chelford
Market on 7 May 2007, which is linked to the Corwen outbreak where
H7N2 was confirmed in poultry on 24 May 2007. All birds on this site
were slaughtered by 5 p.m. on Fri 25 May 2007, and cleansing and
disinfection of the site has now been completed.
Chief Veterinary Officer Dr Christianne Glossop said: "We are very
pleased with today's [29 May 2007] results but must not be complacent
so early in our investigations into the source of this outbreak.
Considerable efforts continue in this complicated tracings exercise.
I repeat my request to any people in Wales who either bought or sold
poultry at Chelford Market in Cheshire on Mon 7 May 2007 or any
poultry keeper in Wales who visited Chelford Market on this date
whose birds have subsequently become ill to contact their local
Animal Health office. All bird keepers throughout Wales should
continue to be vigilant and maintain strict biosecurity precautions,
monitoring their birds for any signs of infectious disease. Again, if
anyone is concerned about the health of their birds, they should
contact Animal Health. The Welsh Assembly Government is working
closely with Animal Health (formerly the State Veterinary Service)
and the National Public Health Service (NPHS) on operations to
control the outbreak in North Wales. The NPHS is managing the human
health side of the outbreak, dealing with issues at a local and
national level, while the Welsh Assembly Government and Animal Health
have a joint team dealing with the bird flu aspects from its base in
Caernarfon."
Chief Medical Officer Tony Jewell said: "The NPHS has provided very
effective operational management of the human health side, working
closely with the NHS in North Wales, local school and community. They
are playing an exemplary role in communicating public health
information and messages and taking proactive action in managing this
outbreak. The Welsh Assembly Government continues to coordinate the
operation, working closely with Whitehall Departments.
--
