[3]
Date: Sat 2 Jun 2007
Source: News BBC [edited]
<http://news.bbc.co.uk/go/pr/fr/-/1/hi/england/6714613.stm>

A ban on showing chickens and ducks at the South of England Show next
week after a case of bird flu in Wales has been lifted.
The show is held every year at Ardingly, West Sussex by the South of
England Agricultural Society, which was founded in 1967. Organizers
of the show had said chickens and ducks would not be shown after a
ruling from Defra. But Defra has now said the restriction has been lifted.
A spokeswoman for Defra said: "There are now no restrictions.
Organizers will be under the general conditions of their license."
[For the conditions, see commentary further].
In Wales, bird flu has been confirmed on a Conwy smallholding, but
tests have since proved negative on a Llyn peninsula farm.
The 1st case of avian flu in Wales was confirmed on 24 May 2007 among
chickens on a smallholding near Corwen in Denbighshire.
The National Public Health Service for Wales (NPHSW) has said the
health risk to the general public is low. In its latest bulletin on
Saturday [2 Jun 2007], it said the number of people -- 252 -- who may
have had contact with the avian flu remained unchanged for the
previous 2 days. Most were now outside of the incubation period.
Dr Marion Lyons, consultant in communicable disease control for the
NPHSW said they remained vigilant. "There are 237 people where there
is now no risk at all of infection or further infection with this
avian flu virus," she said. "This is very reassuring to them. It is
also very reassuring to us, because it demonstrates that the already
low risk of spread is confirmed."
--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Mary Marshall
[The final, negative results of tested samples from the Llyn
peninsula farm, which, reportedly, "had links with the Chelford
Market" (where the birds in the H7N2-infected farm in Conwy had
originated), mean that the identification of the said market as the
source of infection is still in need of confirmation.
DEFRA's updated (1 Jun 2007) guidelines and licensing procedures for
bird gatherings ("arranging the collection together of poultry or
other captive birds from different epidemiological groups at one
location"), including shows, pigeon races and falconry events, are available at
<http://www.defra.gov.uk/animalh/diseases/notifiable/disease/ai/keptbirds/genlicence.htm>.
- Mod.AS]
